{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2515"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2515"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.23,0.28,0.12,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48314"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2515"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48314"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with pain in her left hip after a fall. She was unable to get up off the floor and her husband called an ambulance. She is normally in good health and the only medication she takes is alendronate, together with calcium supplements. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is limited movement of the left hip because of pain, and the left leg appears shortened and externally rotated. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Total hip arthroplasty","Hemiarthroplasty","Open reduction and internal fixation","Closed reduction and internal fixation","Analgesia and supportive care"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained a left intertrochanteric fracture, which is an extracapsular hip fracture. The most appropriate management for this type of fracture is \u003Cstrong\u003Eclosed reduction and internal fixation\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach allows for stabilization of the fracture while minimizing soft tissue damage, as the fracture site does not need to be surgically exposed to be reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal hip arthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for displaced intracapsular fractures in older patients with good pre-fracture mobility and no cognitive impairment. It is not typically used for intertrochanteric fractures as it is more invasive and carries higher risks without additional benefits in this fracture type.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemiarthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is another option for displaced intracapsular fractures, particularly in older patients with lower functional demands. However, it is not appropriate for intertrochanteric fractures, where the femoral head is preserved and can be salvaged with internal fixation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction and internal fixation\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for most intertrochanteric fractures. These fractures can usually be adequately reduced using closed techniques under fluoroscopic guidance, avoiding the additional soft tissue trauma associated with open reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesia and supportive care\u003C/strong\u003E alone (conservative management) is rarely appropriate for hip fractures in ambulatory patients due to high associated morbidity and mortality. Surgical fixation allows for earlier mobilization, reducing the risks of complications such as pneumonia, deep vein thrombosis, and pressure sores.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, closed reduction and internal fixation is the gold standard for managing intertrochanteric fractures. It allows for fracture stabilization, early mobilization, and preservation of the patient\u0027s native hip joint, which is particularly important in this relatively young and healthy 75-year-old patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Extracapsular hip fractures, such as intertrochanteric fractures, should be treated with closed reduction and internal fixation.","The choice of surgical management for hip fractures depends on the fracture classification (intracapsular vs extracapsular) and patient factors.","Conservative management is rarely appropriate for hip fractures in ambulatory patients due to high morbidity and mortality."],"references":["Callaghan JJ, Haidukewych GJ. Subcapital fractures: a changing paradigm. J Bone Joint Surgical Br. 2012; 94: 19-21.","Bhandari M, Swiontkowski M. Management of Acute Hip Fracture. N Engl J Med. 2017; 377:2053-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2515"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16902"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16902"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d9ec5784-9a93-47b6-b5f1-8c044f34242a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media